window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2020>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2020","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"You are provided with a metre rule, a knife-edge, set of masses, inextensible string, retort support and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Place the metre rule on the knife edge. Read and record the point G, where the metre rule balances horizontally, as shown in Fig 1 (a).    (ii) Suspend the metre rule at G with the aid of the string provided and attach the string to the retort support as shown in Fig 1(b). Keep the string attached to this point throughout the experiment.    (iii) Attach the mass Mo at the 80 cm mark of the metre rule. Determine the distance of y from G. Keep Mo at this position throughout the experiment.    (iv) Suspend a mass M = 40 g on the side AG and adjust its position until the metre rule balances horizontally.    (v) Measure and record the distance of x of M from G. Evaluate x\u22121    (vi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of M = 60 g, 80 g, 100 g and 120 g. Measure and record x and evaluate x\u22121 in each case.    (vii) Tabulate the readings.    (viii) Plot a graph of M on the vertical axis and x-1 on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from the origin (0,0).    (ix) Determine the slope, s, of the graph    (x) Given that s = yMo, determine Mo.    (xi) State two precautions taken to obtain accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"(i) G = 50.0 cm, (ii) y = 30.0 cm    S/NM(g)x(cm)x\u22121(cm\u22121)14037.500.02726025.000.04038018.750.055410015.000.067512012.500.080        (ix) s = \u25b3M\u25b3x\u22121\\frac{\u25b3M}{\u25b3x^{-1}}\u25b3x\u22121\u25b3M\u200b = M2\u2212M1x2\u22121\u2212x1\u22121\\frac{M_{2}-M_{1}}{x^{-1}_{2}-x^{-1}_{1}}x2\u22121\u200b\u2212x1\u22121\u200bM2\u200b\u2212M1\u200b\u200b = 120\u2212400.08\u22120.027\\frac{120-40}{0.08-0.027}0.08\u22120.027120\u221240\u200b = 800.053\\frac{80}{0.053}0.05380\u200b = 1509 gcm    s = yMo    1509 = 30Mo    Mo = 150930\\frac{1509}{30}301509\u200b    Mo = 50.3 g    (xi) Precautions:    1. I avoided parallax error by ensuring my eyes were level with the scale markings when reading the metre rule.    2. I ensured the experimental setup was free from draughts by closing windows and doors or switching off fans to prevent unnecessary disturbances.    3. I made sure that all supports in the setup were rigid and firm to avoid vibrations or instability during the experiment.    4. I recorded repeated readings systematically in a table to ensure precision and detect any anomalies in the data.    5. I ensured that the mass did not touch or rest on the table, maintaining proper suspension throughout the experiment.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2020>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2020","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS","question":"Define the moment of a force about a point.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The moment of a force about a point is the measure of the turning effect produced by the force on a body about that point. It is mathematically defined as the product of the force magnitude and the perpendicular distance from the point to the line of action of the force:    Moment = Force \u00d7 Perpendicular\u00a0Distance    The direction of the moment is determined using the right-hand rule and is usually expressed in units such as Newton-meters (Nm).","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2020>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2020","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS","question":"A uniform metre rule is suspended by an inextensible string at its centre of gravity. If a mass of 60 g is placed at the 25 cm mark, what mass should be placed at the 80 cm mark of the metre rule to balance it horizontally?    (Provide your answer to with the unit e.g 123 m)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Sum of clockwise moment  = sum of anticlockwise moment    m x 30 = 60 \u00d7 25    m = 60\u00d72530\\frac{60\u00d725}{30}3060\u00d725\u200b = 50 g","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2020>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2020","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"You are provided with a drawing board, drawing sheets, four optical pins, a triangular glass prism and other necessary materials.  Use the diagram above as a guide to perform the experiment.   (i) Pin the drawing paper onto the drawing board.  (ii) Trace the outline ABC of the triangular prism on the  drawing paper.  (iii) Remove the prism from its trace. Measure and record the refracting angle A.  (iv) Select a point  N  on the side AC of the outline. Draw a straight line MO through  N  and making a glancing angle \u03b2 = 60\u00b0 with the side AC.  (v) Fix two pins at P1 and P2 on the line MN. Replace the prism on its outline.  (vi) Look through the side AB of the prism and fix two other pins at P3 and P4 such that they appear to be in a straight line with the images of the pins at P1 and P2.  (vii) Remove the prism and the pins. Join P3 and P4 with a straight line VT and extend it to meet MO at W.  (viii) Measure and record angles \u03b1 and \u03b3.  (ix) Evaluate \u03b8 = (90 - \u03b2), \u03a6 = (90 -  \u03b1) and \u03bc = (\u03b8 - \u03a6).  (x) Repeat the procedure for four other values of \u03b2 = 65\u00b0, 70\u00b0, 75\u00b0 and 80\u00b0. In each case, measure \u03b1, \u03b3 and evaluate \u03b8, \u03a6 and \u03bc.  (xi) Tabulate the results.  (xii) Plot a graph with \u03b3 on the vertical axis and \u03bc on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from the origin (0,0).  (xiii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph,  (xiv) Determine the intercept, c, on the vertical axis,   (xv) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [Attach your traces to the answer booklet.]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"A = 60\u00b0    S/N\u03b2/\u00b0\u03b1/\u00b0\u03b3/\u00b0\u03b8/\u00b0\u03a6/\u00b0\u03bc/\u00b01606012030300265641102526-1370681002022-247577901513258082801064        (xiii) s = \u25b3\u03b3\u25b3\u03bc\\frac{\u25b3\u03b3}{\u25b3\u03bc}\u25b3\u03bc\u25b3\u03b3\u200b = \u03b32\u2212\u03b31\u03bc2\u2212\u03bc1\\frac{\u03b3_{2}-\u03b3_{1}}{\u03bc_{2}-\u03bc_{1}}\u03bc2\u200b\u2212\u03bc1\u200b\u03b32\u200b\u2212\u03b31\u200b\u200b = 110\u221290\u22121.5\u22122.75\\frac{110-90}{-1.5-2.75}\u22121.5\u22122.75110\u221290\u200b = 20\u22124.25\\frac{20}{-4.25}\u22124.2520\u200b = -4.71    (xiv) Intercept, c = 102.8\u00b0    (xv) Precautions:    1. I ensured that the triangular glass prism was thoroughly cleaned before use to remove any smudges or dust that could affect light refraction.    2. I made sure that the pins were placed upright and firmly fixed into the board to ensure accurate alignment during the experiment.    3. I avoided parallax error by keeping my eyes level with the protractor scale while taking angular measurements.    4. I ensured that the protractor was correctly aligned with the base of the prism for precise angle readings.    5. I handled the prism carefully to avoid chipping or damage that could alter its geometry.    6. I repeated all measurements and documented them to confirm consistency and accuracy.    7. I conducted the experiment in a stable, draught-free environment to prevent disturbances to the setup.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2020>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2020","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Draw to show how a prism is used to invert a beam of light.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2020>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2020","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"A ray of light travelling from glass to air is refracted along the surface of the glass. Calculate the critical angle of the glass. [Refractive index of glass = 1.5]    (Provide your answer to 1 d.p and without the degree symbol)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"sin C = 1n\\frac{1}{n}n1\u200b    sin C = 11.5\\frac{1}{1.5}1.51\u200b    sin C = 0.6667    C = sin-1 (0.667)    C = 41.8\u00b0","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2020>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2020","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"You are provided with a resistance box R, voltmeter, key, cell of e.m.f. E, constantan wire, standard resistor, Rx, an ammeter, and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Measure and record the e.m.f. E of the cell provided.    (ii) Set up the circuit as shown in the diagram above.    (iii) Set R to 1 \u03a9. Close the key, read and record the current I and the corresponding voltage V.    (iv) Repeat the procedure for four other values of R = 2 \u03a9, 4 \u03a9, 6 \u03a9, and 8 \u03a9.    (v) In each case, read and record I and V.    (vi) Tabulate the reading.    (vii) Plot a graph of V on the vertical axis and I on the horizontal axis.    (viii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (ix) State two precautions are taken to ensure accurate results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"E = 3.00 V    R(\u03a9)I(A)V(V)1.00.400.652.00.350.584.00.280.226.00.220.458.00.180.40        (viii) slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.588\u22120.40.4\u22120.238\\frac{0.588-0.4}{0.4-0.238}0.4\u22120.2380.588\u22120.4\u200b = 0.1880.162\\frac{0.188}{0.162}0.1620.188\u200b = 1.16    (ix) Precautions:    1. I ensured that the key was opened between readings or whenever readings were not being taken to prevent unnecessary drainage of the cells.    2. I verified that all electrical connections were tight and secure to minimize energy losses and avoid inconsistent readings.    3. I avoided parallax errors by ensuring my eyes were level with the scale when taking readings on the voltmeter or ammeter.    4. I recorded repeated readings systematically and displayed them clearly in a table to confirm consistency and detect anomalies.    5. I checked for and corrected any zero errors on the voltmeter and ammeter before starting the experiment to ensure accurate measurements.    6. I cleaned the terminals thoroughly to reduce resistance and improve conductivity, ensuring precise results.    7. I ensured the connecting wires were properly insulated and free from breaks to avoid short circuits or unreliable data.    8. I calibrated all instruments beforehand to confirm they were functioning correctly and yielding reliable values.    9. I handled all equipment carefully to avoid damage that could compromise the setup or results.    10. I ensured the experimental area was free from vibrations or disturbances to maintain the integrity of the measurements.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2020>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2020","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"State two advantages of connecting identical cells in parallel.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1. Increased Current Supply: The total current capacity increases since the current is shared between the cells.  2. Improved Battery Life: Parallel connections distribute the load, reducing the strain on individual cells, which prolongs their lifespan.  3. Redundancy: If one cell fails, the circuit can still function using the remaining cells.  4. Stable Voltage Output: The voltage remains the same as that of a single cell, avoiding overloading connected devices.  5. Enhanced Energy Storage: The overall capacity of the battery system (in ampere-hours) is increased.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2020>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2020","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"State two factors to consider in choosing the material for the design of a resistor","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1. Resistivity: The material should have a specific resistivity suitable for the desired resistance value.  2. Temperature Coefficient: A low temperature coefficient ensures stability of resistance with temperature changes.  3. Durability: The material should withstand environmental factors like humidity and oxidation.  4. Power Dissipation: The material should handle the expected power without degrading or overheating.  5. Cost: The material should be economically viable for the intended application.  6. Mechanical Strength: The material must endure physical stress during manufacturing and usage.  7. Thermal Conductivity: Efficient heat dissipation is essential to avoid damage under high loads.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];